Interesting Facts Revealed about Ford GoBike¶

*by Lin Chen*¶

Investigation Overview¶

Based on the dataset provided, we could have a glimpse of how the regional public bicycle sharing system runs in California's San Francisco Bay Area, as well as biking preferences in terms of location, time and duration, from users under different age and gender groups.

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset contains detailed information of all Ford GoBike tours in Feb 2019, at cities of San Francisco, San Jose and Oakland respectively. Time and location for starting point and destination, gender and age for users, as well as some other features are provided for each bike tour.

Biking Duration¶

  • Due to some super long-time biking activities, the duration distribution is right-skewed.
  • In February 2019, there were 56 bike tours lasted longer than 16 hours, the longest one lasted for almost 24 hours.

  • However, around 60% of bike tours only have duration between 5 and 15 minutes.
  • Median for biking duration is 8.6 minutes, while the average duration is 12.1 minutes due to those large outliers.
    • Longest bike tour: 23.73 hr
Bike tours longer than 16 hr happened 56 times in Feb 2019
Bike tours longer than 4 hr: 0.16 %
Bike tours longer than 1 hr: 0.93 %
Bike tours longer than 30 min: 3.69 %
--------------------------------------------
Bike tours between 5 min and 15 min: 59.31 %

    Day for Biking¶

    There are 28 days in February 2019, and each day in a week contains 4 different days, so it's fair to carry out a direct comparison between 7 different days in a week without using weighted averages.

  • Based on the pie chart, only 16.85% of the recorded biking tours started on weekends.
  • Thursday has most biking tours, while Saturday and Sunday have the least.
  • Average bike tour activities on a single weekday is around 2 times of biking tours on a single weekend.
  • There are more long-time biking tours happened during weekends, which resulted in higher Q3 values.

    • Outliers are removed in the boxplot, since there are too much of them.

    On each weekend, there are 15440 bike tours on average.
On each weekday, there are 30467 bike tours on average.
--------------------------------------------------------------
Bike tours on a weekday is approximately 2 times of a weekend.

    Hour for Biking¶

  • During weekdays, there are two clear peaks on histogram, at 8 and 17 respectively.
  • It's not surprising since 8 AM and 5 PM are two rush hours for people going to work/school and back home.

  • During weekends, there is only one vague peak on histogram at around 13 and 14.
  • There is more flexibility for people's schedule on weekend, and the distribution curve looks more smooth.
  • 1 or 2 PM after lunch are be the busiest biking hours, perhaps due to more sunshine and high temperature for days in February.

    • Places for Biking¶

    Part 1¶

  • Based on the longitudes and latitudes provided, bike stations are located in three cities: San Francisco, Oakland and San Jose.
  • For each single bike tour, stations for start and end are all in same city, which means nobody ride bike from one city to another.

  • Total bike tours: 73% in San Francisco, 23% in Oakland, 4% in San Jose.
  • Bike station numbers: 47% in San Francisco, 39% in Oakland, 14% in San Jose.
  • Based on the violin plot, bike stations in San Francisco are busiest, followed by Oakland and then San Jose.
    • Average bike tours for each station:

    Places for Biking¶

    Part 3¶

  • In terms of median values for biking duration, San Francisco is longest, followed by San Jose and Oakland.
  • However for average values, though users in San Francisco biking for longest time, this time Oakland ranks the second.
  • The reason for different rankings of medians and means is, biking duration distribution for Oakland is relatively right-skewed than others.

    • Outliers are removed in the boxplot, since there are too much of them.

    GoBike User Age¶

    For GoBiker users who were born before 1930, they will be older than 90 years old in Feb 2019. Therefore, those information shall be temperarily removed for age analysis, since users might provide wrong age values.

  • The average age for users is 34 years old (born in 1985).
  • Young generations born between 1985 and 1995 are main users of GoBike, with age from 24 to 34.
  • Generally speaking, under a younger age, the maximum biking duration tends to be longer.

    • GoBike User Gender¶

    Part 1¶

    For GoBiker users who were born before 1930, they will be older than 90 years old in Feb 2019. Therefore, those information shall be temperarily removed for age analysis, since users might provide wrong age values.

  • The average age for users is 34 years old (born in 1985).
  • Young generations born between 1985 and 1995 are main users of GoBike, with age from 24 to 34.
  • Generally speaking, under a younger age, the maximum biking duration tends to be longer.
  • There are least percentage for female and "other" users in San Jose, perhaps due to high male percentage for IT industry.
    • Male percentage for users:
--------------------------
San Francisco: 75.38 %
Oakland: 69.76 %
San Jose: 86.52 %

    GoBike User Gender¶

    Part 2¶

  • Surprisingly, female users biking for longer time than male users, both on average or median values.
  • The users who put 'other' on gender actually biking for longest time, which is also quite interesting.
  • Since 75% users are recorded as men, their average biking duration might be decreased due to lots of small values under male users.

    • Outliers are removed in the boxplot, since there are too much of them.

    GoBike User Type¶

  • Majority of GoBike users are subscribers, for almost 90%.
  • However, biking durations for customers are much higher than subscribers, no matter which city they are in.
  • Users usually subscribe for a much lower rate, thus subscribers are frequent users.
  • Customers only use GoBike for temporarily, to compensate for their higher payment per ride, they tend to biking for relatively long time.

    • GoBike Share¶

  • Majority of GoBike trips are not shared, for almost 90%.
  • Only subscribers could share for all trip, customers can't.
  • During weekends, biking durations for unshared trips are apparently longer than shared trips and trips on weekdays.

    • More long-time biking tours happened during weekends since people have more free time, and those users also have higher chance to be customers rather than subscribers, which resulted in longer unshared trip durations during weekends.

    GoBike Stations¶

  • Average bike tours per station is 1114.
  • Monthly bike tour numbers range from 8 to 8401.

The loneliest station id is 344, with bike tours of 8, in the city of San Francisco
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Average bike tours per station is 1114

    GoBike Stations¶

    Part 2¶

  • For certain station, bike flow in if chosen as destination for a biking tour, and bike flow out if chosen as starting point.
  • High positive net bike flow value indicates a bike surplus.
  • Low negative net bike flow value indicates a bike shortage.

  • Majority of stations don't have severe bike shortage or surplus, since their net bike flow in a month were between -100 to 100.
  • However, some stations have severe bike surplus or bike shortage.
  • The good new is, for all stations in each city listed, sums of their net bike flow are all 0, which means no bike got stolen.

    • Stations Under Severe Bike Surplus:

id: 67, surplus: 1313, city: San Francisco
id: 21, surplus: 752, city: San Francisco
id: 15, surplus: 658, city: San Francisco
-------------------------------------------
Stations Under Severe Bike Shortage:

id: 243, shortage: -646, city: Oakland
id: 253, shortage: -324, city: Oakland
id: 22, shortage: -259, city: San Francisco

    Busiest Station: No.67¶

  • No.67 bike station in San Francisco has the most bike tour numbers.
  • Five bike stations have strong connection to No.67, and they are: No.90, No.58, No.89, No.61 and No.21.
  • For the stations mentioned above, lots of bikes from No.67 visited them, and lots of bikes from them visited No.67.

    • Busiest Bike: No.4794¶

  • Bike No.4794 is the busiest one, with 191 tours involved.
  • There are 83 "unlucky" bikes that were only used for once.
  • The good news is, all bikes was used for at least once.
  • On average, bike was used for 40 times in Feb 2019.

    • Conclusions¶

  • Ford GoBike is most frequently used in San Francisco.
  • Few bikes and stations were very frequently used, but most of them were not.
  • On average, a bike can be used 1.3 times per day, a station can be used 35 times a day.
  • Few popular bike stations have severe bike shortage or surplus, measures needed to be carried out to solve the inequality.
  • Most people ride bike for 8-10 minutes each time, and 75% users are young male between 25-35 years old.
  • But, there are also people ride bikes for more than 10 hours, regular quality check is needed based on bike's frequency to be used.
